04720nam a2200577Ia 9780231559546DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315595467 a10.7312/helt212762doi  a(DE-B1597)690089  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE184.6b.H45 2024 7aLIT0040402bisacsh04a026/.3231196073223/eng/202310121 aHelton, Laura, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScattered and Fugitive Things :bHow Black Collectors Created Archives and Remade History /cLaura Helton. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBlack Lives in the Diaspora: Past / Present / Future00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Value, Order, Risk—Experiments in Black Archiving -- t1. Thinking Black, Collecting Black: Schomburg’s Desiderata and the Radical World of Black Bibliophiles -- t2. A “History of the Negro in Scrapbooks”: The Gumby Book Studio’s Ephemeral Assemblies -- t3. Defiant Libraries: Virginia Lee and the Secrets Kept by Good Bookladies -- t4. Unauthorized Inquiries: Dorothy Porter’s Wayward Catalog -- t5. A Space for Black Study: The Hall Branch Library and the Historians Who Never Wrote -- t6. Mobilizing Manuscripts: L. D. Reddick and Black Archival Politics -- tEpilogue -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the first half of the twentieth century, a group of collectors and creators dedicated themselves to documenting the history of African American life. At a time when dominant institutions cast doubt on the value or even the idea of Black history, these bibliophiles, scrapbookers, and librarians created an enduring set of African diasporic archives. In building these institutions and amassing abundant archival material, they also reshaped Black public culture, animating inquiry into the nature and meaning of Black history.Scattered and Fugitive Things tells the stories of these Black collectors, traveling from the parlors of the urban north to HBCU reading rooms and branch libraries in the Jim Crow south. Laura E. Helton chronicles the work of six key figures: bibliophile Arturo Schomburg, scrapbook maker Alexander Gumby, librarians Virginia Lee and Vivian Harsh, curator Dorothy Porter, and historian L. D. Reddick. Drawing on overlooked sources such as book lists and card catalogs, she reveals the risks collectors took to create Black archives. This book also explores the social life of collecting, highlighting the communities that used these collections from the South Side of Chicago to Roanoke, Virginia. In each case, Helton argues, archiving was alive in the present, a site of intellectual experiment, creative abundance, and political possibility. Offering new ways to understand Black intellectual and literary history, Scattered and Fugitive Things reveals Black collecting as a radical critical tradition that reimagines past, present, and future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican American book collectorsxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican American historiansxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican American intellectualsxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican American librariansxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxArchivesxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual lifey20th century. 0aArchiveszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aArchivistszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLibrariesxSpecial collectionsxAfrican Americans. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / African-American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/helt2127640uhttps://www